#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:4
msgid "How to run doctests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:6
msgid ""
"By default, all files matching the ``test*.txt`` pattern will be run through "
"the python standard :mod:`doctest` module.  You can change the pattern by "
"issuing:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:10
msgid "pytest --doctest-glob=\"*.rst\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:14
msgid ""
"on the command line. :option:`--doctest-glob` can be given multiple times in "
"the command-line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:16
msgid "If you then have a text file like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:18
msgid ""
"# content of test_example.txt\n"
"\n"
"hello this is a doctest\n"
">>> x = 3\n"
">>> x\n"
"3"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:27
msgid "then you can just invoke ``pytest`` directly:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:29
msgid ""
"$ pytest\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-9.x.y, pluggy-1.x.y\n"
"rootdir: /home/sweet/project\n"
"collected 1 item\n"
"\n"
"test_example.txt .                                                   [100%]\n"
"\n"
"============================ 1 passed in 0.12s ============================="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:41
msgid ""
"By default, pytest will collect ``test*.txt`` files looking for doctest "
"directives, but you can pass additional globs using the :option:`--doctest-"
"glob` option (multi-allowed)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:44
msgid ""
"In addition to text files, you can also execute doctests directly from "
"docstrings of your classes and functions, including from test modules:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:47
msgid ""
"# content of mymodule.py\n"
"def something():\n"
"    \"\"\"a doctest in a docstring\n"
"    >>> something()\n"
"    42\n"
"    \"\"\"\n"
"    return 42"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:57
msgid ""
"$ pytest --doctest-modules\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-9.x.y, pluggy-1.x.y\n"
"rootdir: /home/sweet/project\n"
"collected 2 items\n"
"\n"
"mymodule.py .                                                        [ 50%]\n"
"test_example.txt .                                                   [100%]\n"
"\n"
"============================ 2 passed in 0.12s ============================="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:70
msgid ""
"You can make these changes permanent in your project by putting them into a "
"configuration file like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:73
msgid ""
"# content of pytest.toml\n"
"[pytest]\n"
"addopts = [\"--doctest-modules\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:80
msgid "Encoding"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:82
msgid ""
"The default encoding is **UTF-8**, but you can specify the encoding that "
"will be used for those doctest files using the :confval:`doctest_encoding` "
"configuration option:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:88
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"doctest_encoding = \"latin1\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:95
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"doctest_encoding = latin1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:103
msgid "Using 'doctest' options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:105
msgid ""
"Python's standard :mod:`doctest` module provides some :ref:`options <python:"
"option-flags-and-directives>` to configure the strictness of doctest tests. "
"In pytest, you can enable those flags using the configuration file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:109
msgid ""
"For example, to make pytest ignore trailing whitespaces and ignore lengthy "
"exception stack traces you can just write:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:114
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"doctest_optionflags = [\"NORMALIZE_WHITESPACE\", \"IGNORE_EXCEPTION_DETAIL\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:121
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"doctest_optionflags = NORMALIZE_WHITESPACE IGNORE_EXCEPTION_DETAIL"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:126
msgid ""
"Alternatively, options can be enabled by an inline comment in the doc test "
"itself:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:129
msgid ""
">>> something_that_raises()  # doctest: +IGNORE_EXCEPTION_DETAIL\n"
"Traceback (most recent call last):\n"
"ValueError: ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:135
msgid "pytest also introduces new options:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:137
msgid ""
"``ALLOW_UNICODE``: when enabled, the ``u`` prefix is stripped from unicode "
"strings in expected doctest output. This allows doctests to run in Python 2 "
"and Python 3 unchanged."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:141
msgid ""
"``ALLOW_BYTES``: similarly, the ``b`` prefix is stripped from byte strings "
"in expected doctest output."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:144
msgid ""
"``NUMBER``: when enabled, floating-point numbers only need to match as far "
"as the precision you have written in the expected doctest output. The "
"numbers are compared using :func:`pytest.approx` with relative tolerance "
"equal to the precision. For example, the following output would only need to "
"match to 2 decimal places when comparing ``3.14`` to ``pytest.approx(math."
"pi, rel=10**-2)``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:151
msgid ""
">>> math.pi\n"
"3.14"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:154
msgid ""
"If you wrote ``3.1416`` then the actual output would need to match to "
"approximately 4 decimal places; and so on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:157
msgid ""
"This avoids false positives caused by limited floating-point precision, like "
"this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:160
msgid ""
"Expected:\n"
"    0.233\n"
"Got:\n"
"    0.23300000000000001"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:165
msgid ""
"``NUMBER`` also supports lists of floating-point numbers -- in fact, it "
"matches floating-point numbers appearing anywhere in the output, even inside "
"a string! This means that it may not be appropriate to enable globally in "
"``doctest_optionflags`` in your configuration file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:174
msgid "Continue on failure"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:176
msgid ""
"By default, pytest would report only the first failure for a given doctest. "
"If you want to continue the test even when you have failures, do:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:179
msgid "pytest --doctest-modules --doctest-continue-on-failure"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:185
msgid "Output format"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:187
msgid ""
"You can change the diff output format on failure for your doctests by using "
"one of the standard doctest module's format options (see :data:`python:"
"doctest.REPORT_UDIFF`, :data:`python:doctest.REPORT_CDIFF`, :data:`python:"
"doctest.REPORT_NDIFF`, :data:`python:doctest.REPORT_ONLY_FIRST_FAILURE`):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:192
msgid ""
"pytest --doctest-modules --doctest-report none\n"
"pytest --doctest-modules --doctest-report udiff\n"
"pytest --doctest-modules --doctest-report cdiff\n"
"pytest --doctest-modules --doctest-report ndiff\n"
"pytest --doctest-modules --doctest-report only_first_failure"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:202
msgid "pytest-specific features"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:204
msgid ""
"Some features are provided to make writing doctests easier or with better "
"integration with your existing test suite. Keep in mind however that by "
"using those features you will make your doctests incompatible with the "
"standard ``doctests`` module."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:209
msgid "Using fixtures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:211
msgid "It is possible to use fixtures using the ``getfixture`` helper:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:213
msgid ""
"# content of example.rst\n"
">>> tmp = getfixture('tmp_path')\n"
">>> ...\n"
">>>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:220
msgid ""
"Note that the fixture needs to be defined in a place visible by pytest, for "
"example, a `conftest.py` file or plugin; normal python files containing "
"docstrings are not normally scanned for fixtures unless explicitly "
"configured by :confval:`python_files`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:224
msgid ""
"Also, the :ref:`usefixtures <usefixtures>` mark and fixtures marked as :ref:"
"`autouse <autouse>` are supported when executing text doctest files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:231
msgid "'doctest_namespace' fixture"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:233
msgid ""
"The ``doctest_namespace`` fixture can be used to inject items into the "
"namespace in which your doctests run. It is intended to be used within your "
"own fixtures to provide the tests that use them with context."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:237
msgid ""
"``doctest_namespace`` is a standard ``dict`` object into which you place the "
"objects you want to appear in the doctest namespace:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:240
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"import numpy\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(autouse=True)\n"
"def add_np(doctest_namespace):\n"
"    doctest_namespace[\"np\"] = numpy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:251
msgid "which can then be used in your doctests directly:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:253
msgid ""
"# content of numpy.py\n"
"def arange():\n"
"    \"\"\"\n"
"    >>> a = np.arange(10)\n"
"    >>> len(a)\n"
"    10\n"
"    \"\"\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:263
msgid ""
"Note that like the normal ``conftest.py``, the fixtures are discovered in "
"the directory tree conftest is in. Meaning that if you put your doctest with "
"your source code, the relevant conftest.py needs to be in the same directory "
"tree. Fixtures will not be discovered in a sibling directory tree!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:268
msgid "Skipping tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:270
msgid ""
"For the same reasons one might want to skip normal tests, it is also "
"possible to skip tests inside doctests."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:273
msgid ""
"To skip a single check inside a doctest you can use the standard :data:"
"`doctest.SKIP` directive:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:276
msgid ""
"def test_random(y):\n"
"    \"\"\"\n"
"    >>> random.random()  # doctest: +SKIP\n"
"    0.156231223\n"
"\n"
"    >>> 1 + 1\n"
"    2\n"
"    \"\"\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:287
msgid "This will skip the first check, but not the second."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:289
msgid ""
"pytest also allows using the standard pytest functions :func:`pytest.skip` "
"and :func:`pytest.xfail` inside doctests, which might be useful because you "
"can then skip/xfail tests based on external conditions:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:294
msgid ""
">>> import sys, pytest\n"
">>> if sys.platform.startswith('win'):\n"
"...     pytest.skip('this doctest does not work on Windows')\n"
"...\n"
">>> import fcntl\n"
">>> ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:303
msgid ""
"However using those functions is discouraged because it reduces the "
"readability of the docstring."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:308
msgid ""
":func:`pytest.skip` and :func:`pytest.xfail` behave differently depending if "
"the doctests are in a Python file (in docstrings) or a text file containing "
"doctests intermingled with text:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:312
msgid ""
"Python modules (docstrings): the functions only act in that specific "
"docstring, letting the other docstrings in the same module execute as normal."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:315
msgid ""
"Text files: the functions will skip/xfail the checks for the rest of the "
"entire file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:320
msgid "Alternatives"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:322
msgid ""
"While the built-in pytest support provides a good set of functionalities for "
"using doctests, if you use them extensively you might be interested in those "
"external packages which add many more features, and include pytest "
"integration:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:326
msgid ""
"`pytest-doctestplus <https://github.com/scientific-python/pytest-"
"doctestplus>`__: provides advanced doctest support and enables the testing "
"of reStructuredText (\".rst\") files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/doctest.rst:329
msgid ""
"`Sybil <https://sybil.readthedocs.io>`__: provides a way to test examples in "
"your documentation by parsing them from the documentation source and "
"evaluating the parsed examples as part of your normal test run."
msgstr ""
